INSTRUCTIONS- Answer all questions.- Use a black or dark blue pen. You may use an HB pencil for any diagrams or graphs.- Write your name, centre number and candidate number in the boxes at the top of the page.- Write your answer to each question in the space provided.- Do not use an erasable pen or correction fluid.- Do not write on any bar codes.- If additional space is needed, you should use the lined page at the end of this booklet; the question number or numbers must be clearly shown.- You should use a calculator where appropriate.- You must show all necessary working clearly; no marks will be given for unsupported answers from a calculator.- Give non- exact numerical answers correct to 3 significant figures, or 1 decimal place for angles in degrees, unless a different level of accuracy is specified in the question.- Where a numerical value for the acceleration due to gravity \((g)\) is needed, use \(10 \text{m s}^{- 2}\) .

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 73, 920, 108]]<|/det|>
A lorry of mass \(16 000\mathrm{kg}\) is travelling along a straight horizontal road. The engine of the lorry is working at constant power. The work done by the driving force in \(10\mathrm{s}\) is \(750 000\mathrm{J}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 120, 146, 138]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 120, 448, 138]]<|/det|>
Find the power of the lorry's engine.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 120, 920, 138]]<|/det|>
<mark>[1]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[111, 329, 143, 348]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 329, 769, 348]]<|/det|>
There is a constant resistance force acting on the lorry of magnitude \(2400 \mathrm{N}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 361, 739, 380]]<|/det|>
Find the acceleration of the lorry at an instant when its speed is \(25 \mathrm{m s}^{-1}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 361, 920, 380]]<|/det|>
<mark>[3]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 73, 94, 92]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>image<|/ref|><|det|>[[267, 82, 767, 268]]<|/det|>


<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 285, 920, 351]]<|/det|>
The diagram shows the vertical cross-section of a surface. \(A, B\) and \(C\) are three points on the cross- section. The level of \(B\) is \(h\) m above the level of \(A\). The level of \(C\) is \(0.5\) m below the level of \(A\). A particle of mass \(0.2 \mathrm{kg}\) is projected up the slope from \(A\) with initial speed \(5 \mathrm{m} \mathrm{s}^{- 1}\). The particle remains in contact with the surface as it travels from \(A\) to \(C\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 363, 146, 381]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[154, 363, 920, 396]]<|/det|>
Given that the particle reaches \(B\) with a speed of \(3 \mathrm{m} \mathrm{s}^{- 1}\) and that there is no resistance force, find \(h\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 380, 920, 398]]<|/det|>
<mark>[3]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 73, 148, 91]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 73, 920, 107]]<|/det|>
It is given instead that there is a resistance force and that the particle does 3.1 J of work against the resistance force as it travels from \(A\) to \(C\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 120, 544, 138]]<|/det|>
Find the speed of the particle when it reaches \(C\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 120, 920, 138]]<|/det|>
<mark>[3]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 75, 92, 92]]<|/det|>
<label>4</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 73, 920, 125]]<|/det|>
A cyclist travels along a straight road with constant acceleration. He passes through points \(A, B\) and \(C\). The cyclist takes 2 seconds to travel along each of the sections \(AB\) and \(BC\) and passes through \(B\) with speed \(4.5 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\). The distance \(AB\) is \(\frac{4}{5}\) of the distance \(BC\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 139, 148, 156]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[158, 138, 438, 156]]<|/det|>
Find the acceleration of the cyclist.

<mark>[5]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 303, 885, 322]]<|/det|>
Coplanar forces, of magnitudes \(F \mathrm{~N}, 3 \mathrm{~N}, 6 \mathrm{~N}\) and \(4 \mathrm{~N}\), act at a point \(P\), as shown in the diagram.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 335, 148, 352]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 333, 920, 367]]<|/det|>
Given that \(\alpha = 60\), and that the resultant of the four forces is in the direction of the \(3 \mathrm{~N}\) force, find \(F\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 349, 920, 368]]<|/det|>
<mark>[3]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 73, 148, 92]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 73, 792, 92]]<|/det|>
Given instead that the four forces are in equilibrium, find the values of \(F\) and \(\alpha\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 73, 920, 92]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 73, 920, 107]]<|/det|>
At the instant when the brakes are applied, the car has speed \(22 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{- 1}\). At this instant the car is \(17.5 \mathrm{~m}\) away from a stationary van, which is directly in front of the car.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 120, 566, 139]]<|/det|>
Show that the car hits the van at a speed of \(8 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{- 1}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 120, 920, 139]]<|/det|>
<mark>[2]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 528, 186, 546]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[158, 528, 920, 562]]<|/det|>
After the collision, the van starts to move with speed \(5 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{- 1}\) and the car and trailer continue moving in the same direction with speed \(2 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{- 1}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 574, 361, 593]]<|/det|>
Find the mass of the van.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 574, 920, 593]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 73, 920, 108]]<|/det|>
A particle moves in a straight line through the point \(O\). The displacement of the particle from \(O\) at time \(t\) s is \(s \mathrm{~m}\), where

<|ref|>equation<|/ref|><|det|>[[368, 107, 630, 127]]<|/det|>
\[s = t^{2} - 3t + 2\qquad \mathrm{for} 0\leqslant t\leqslant 6,\]

<|ref|>equation<|/ref|><|det|>[[368, 131, 598, 163]]<|/det|>
\[s = \frac{24}{t} -\frac{t^2}{4} + 25\qquad \mathrm{for} t\geqslant 6.\]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 178, 146, 196]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[158, 178, 920, 212]]<|/det|>
Find the value of \(t\) when the particle is instantaneously at rest during the first 6 seconds of its motion.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 196, 920, 214]]<|/det|>
<mark>[2]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 495, 601, 515]]<|/det|>
At \(t = 6\), the particle hits a barrier at a point \(P\) and rebounds.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 528, 148, 546]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 528, 920, 562]]<|/det|>
Find the velocity with which the particle arrives at \(P\) and also the velocity with which the particle leaves \(P\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 543, 920, 562]]<|/det|>
<mark>[3]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 73, 816, 92]]<|/det|>
